This one seems good to go though right?

@adrianhopebailie
Could you help me answer the questions in my previous comment ?
Thanks in advance !

ilp-core/src/main/java/org/interledger/core/InterledgerProtocolException.java

```
public String toString(){
  return interledgerRejectPacket.toString();
}
```

As discussed in #89 I think this should include the value of this.getMessage()

> Does the same hold for the 2 other packet types of ILP v4 (InterledgerPreparePacket and InterledgerFulfillPacket)?

Yes, in all packets the `data` field is _not_ optional, it must always be there. However, it can be empty, which should be the default setting.

Should look like this in the `AbstractInterledgerRejectPacket`:

```
   @Override
   @Default
   public byte[] getData(){
     return new byte[0];
   }
```

You're both welcome :+1: 

@sappenin It's ok, I'll write explicit constant names in future contributions.

About more explicit error messages upon an `InterledgerAddress#check()` reject, I opened https://github.com/hyperledger/quilt/issues/104. Let me know if it's not so good for visitors to open issues: I believe one can't add labels to them when having that role (i.e. tagging as `evolution`, `winter games`, `foo`).

From @adrianhopebailie, this should work:

```
  final String message = "message";
  final String prefix = "prefix";

  // Construct an Ed25519 Fulfillment (which signs "message")
  KeyPair ed25519KeyPair = constructEdDsaKeyPair();
  Signature edDsaSigner = new EdDSAEngine(sha512Digest);
  edDsaSigner.initSign(ed25519KeyPair.getPrivate());
  edDsaSigner.update((prefix + message).getBytes());
  byte[] edDsaSignature = edDsaSigner.sign();
  Ed25519Sha256Fulfillment signatureFulfillment = Ed25519Sha256Fulfillment((EdDSAPublicKey) ed25519KeyPair.getPublic(), edDsaSignature);

  // Construct a Prefix Fulfillment
  PrefixSha256Fulfillment prefixFulfillment = new PrefixSha256Fulfillment(
            prefix.getBytes(), 100, signatureFulfillment
   );
  PrefixSha256Condition prefixCondition = prefixFulfillment.getCondition();

  assertTrue(prefixFulfillment.verify(prefixCondition, message.getBytes()); 
```

@adrianhopebailie That should be fine now: I refreshed the PR branch from `hyperledger:master` and refactored it accordingly (crypto-conditions classes became immutables in the meantime).

I didn't get why `ThresholdSha256ConditionTest.java` conflicted, anyway.

So far, the commits tree is not clean for this PR. When it'll be approved, do you have the ability to squash it in 1 commit on `hyperledger:master`? (I hope so :p)

@nathanawmk  Hyperledger project requires you to sign your commits (git commit --signoff ...) .

Try git reset HEAD~2, git commit -s -m, git push --force to merge these changes into a single commit and signing it before pushing it again

Otherwise the addition to the README looks good to me!. This is a typical problem for new installs.

@controlsurface this looks great thanks.

Please can you amend the commit to include your signature and then push it again. That will get the DCO check to pass.

You should be able to simply do a `git commit --amend -s` then `git push --force`

@rizwantanoli this still seems to be broken for some reason. Sorry, that this is proving to be a PIA.

Can I suggest trying to rebase this on `upstream master` and squashing all your changes into a single commit then  pushing that up to `rizwantanoli:master` and see if that solves the issue.

If you are still struggling, let me know.

@adrianhopebailie tried various things but no avail. I installed the checkstyle plugin for eclipse and ran that as well. It didn't give me any errors (warnings on some imports in some files not being in proper order) and the maven build for checkstyle ran successfully as well.
At this point, I am thinking it might have had something to do with how GitHub is maybe treating my line endings when checking-in/checking out or it could be encoding - although I didn't change any encoding options or settings.
I will go ahead and revert these changes and see if the diff only highlights what I changed vs. entire file
